weth在英国可瓦爾结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。她去世于1429年9月8日在她的家乡享年27岁。"},"hr":{"1402–8 September 1429":"1402.–8. rujna 1429.","1402–1429":"1402.–1429","1410–Female":"1410–preminula","1403–1444":"1403.–1444","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1426–1497":"1426–1497","–Male":"preminuo","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1380–Female":"1380–preminula","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","8 September 1426":"8. rujna 1426.","8 September 1429":"8. rujna 1429.","1426":"1426","1403":"1403.","1402":"1402.","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420.","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","26 August 1419":"26. kolovoza 1419.","1429":"1429","1405":"1405.","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Fentongollan, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Trenoweth, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"cs":{"1402–8 September 1429":"1402–8. září 1429","1402–1429":"1402–1429","1410–Female":"1410–Zesnulá","1403–1444":"1403–1444","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1426–1497":"1426–1497","–Male":"Zesnulý","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1380–Female":"1380–Zesnulá","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","8 September 1426":"8. září 1426","8 September 1429":"8. září 1429","1426":"1426","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","26 August 1419":"26. srpna 1419","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Anglie","Fentongollan, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Anglie","Trenoweth, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Anglie","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Anglie"},"da":{"1402–8 September 1429":"1402–8. september 1429","1402–1429":"1402–1429","1410–Female":"1410–Afdød","1403–1444":"1403–1444","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1426–1497":"1426–1497","–Male":"Afdød","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1380–Female":"1380–Afdød","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","8 September 1426":"8. september 1426","8 September 1429":"8. september 1429","1426":"1426","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","26 August 1419":"26. august 1419","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Fentongollan, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Trenoweth, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"nl":{"1402–8 September 1429":"1402–8 september 1429","1402–1429":"1402–1429","1410–Female":"1410–Overleden","1403–1444":"1403–1444","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1426–1497":"1426–1497","–Male":"Overleden","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1380–Female":"1380–Overleden","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","8 September 1426":"8 september 1426","8 September 1429":"8 september 1429","1426":"1426","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","26 August 1419":"26 augustus 1419","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Fentongollan, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Trenoweth, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1402–8 September 1429":"1402–8 September 1429","1402–1429":"1402–1429","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1403–1444":"1403–1444","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1426–1497":"1426–1497","–Male":"Deceased","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","8 September 1426":"8 September 1426","8 September 1429":"8 September 1429","1426":"1426","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1452":"1452","26 August 1419":"26 August 1419","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Fentongollan, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Trenoweth, , Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nanfan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, Haitian, and Mauritian: nickname from French <i>fanfan</i> ‘baby, (little) child’. This surname is very rare in France. It was brought to the US mostly from Haiti, and also from the Dominican Republic, where it is of Haitian origin and rare."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Nanfan was born in 1402, in Cornwall, England, her father, James Nanfan, was 33 and her mother, Margaret Megre, was 23. She married John Trenoweth in 1420, in Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 8 September 1429, in her hometown, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1402–8 September 1429":"1402–8. september 1429","1402–1429":"1402–1429","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1403–1444":"1403–1444","1410–1452":"1410–1452","1426–1497":"1426–1497","–Male":"Surnud","1370–1460":"1370–1460","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1460":"1460","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","8 September 1426":"8. sept